                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 511.4A1/1481.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Delegate
                            <persName type="to">Van Dyke</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 24, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your June 23. You may inform Dr. Loudon, Minister for Foreign Affairs, that if it
                    is not possible to secure the agreement of all the powers to put the Convention
                    into effect, it would seem to this Government to be especially desirable that,
                    in view of Chapter Four of the International Opium Convention, all those powers
                    having treaty relations with China should agree to put the Convention into
                    effect. If in your opinion and in the opinion of the Netherlands Government the
                    Convention is likely to become abortive, you may concur in the proposal of the
                    Netherlands Delegation to put into effect the Convention among as many powers as
                    are disposed to assent to it, but in any case it should be made effective by all
                    the powers that have signed. You may inform the Conference of the attitude of
                    this Government and at the same time express this Government’s hope that the
                    dissenting powers will in due course express their willingness to cooperate with
                    the signatory powers by ratifying the Convention, and provision should be made
                    for subsequent ratifications as they may occur.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
